				\begin{document}$$\begin{array}{*{20}{c}} {\alpha {\mathrm{h}}\nu = {\mathrm{A}}\left( {{\mathrm{h}}\nu - E_G} \right)^{1/n}} \end{array}$$\end{document}where “A” is proportionality constant; “hν” is photon energy displayed in “eV” and “Eg” refers to the bandgap of the material. Though the question on the nature of the CuSCN bandgap remains open, we consider it direct (n = 2) as suggested in most cases24,33. The linear region is extrapolated to the x-axis. The enlarged fitting with thinner films is shown in the inset. The optical bandgaps for all CuSCN films is 3.84–3.95 eV, which agrees with reported results for p-type CuSCN (Supplementary Fig. 16)19,24,33. A bandgap of 2.02 eV was found for Cu2O with the above method (Supplementary Fig. 17). The reflectance data were also collected showing negligible reflection from the CuSCN films (Supplementary Fig. 18).

